+sub_section( 'How to Translate a Theme?' )

	h4 Using <a href="https://poedit.net/">Poedit</a> software

	ol
		li
			p Create a copy of the original <code>#{config.slug}/languages/#{config.slug}.pot</code> file.

		li
			p Rename the copied file now: add hyphen followed with <a href="https://translate.wordpress.org/">your language code locale</a>, and change file extension to "po". <br>(So, the British English file would be named <code>#{config.slug}-en_GB.po</code>.)

		li
			p Use <a href="https://poedit.net/"><strong>Poedit</strong></a> to translate the file and export (save) translation in "mo" file format.

		li
			p Upload translated <code>#{config.slug}-en_GB.mo</code> file into your WordPress languages directory, into <code>themes</code> folder (such as <code>/wp-content/languages/themes/#{config.slug}-en_GB.mo</code> (if the <code>themes</code> folder does not exist in your WordPress languages directory, create it).

			+danger( 'Don\'t loose your files!' )
				p When you update the theme, all custom translation files will be deleted from <code>/wp-content/themes/#{config.slug}/languages</code> folder. Do not place your custom translation files into that folder! Basically, you should never modify the theme files and folders &rarr; use a <a href="#child-theme">child theme</a> instead.


	h4 Translating in WordPress admin

	p If you would like translate the theme directly in your WordPress dashboard you need to use a specialized plugin for that. Please install and activate <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/loco-translate/"><strong>Loco Translate</strong> plugin</a>.

	p For instructions on how to use the plugin please refer to <a href="https://localise.biz/wordpress/plugin/beginners">beginner's guide</a> and/or <a href="https://localise.biz/wordpress/plugin/overview">technical overview</a>.
